## Weekly Rhythms: Cadence That Drives Progress

### The Weekly Planning Practice

<Callout type="info" title="Intentional Rhythm">
Remote teams lose the natural rhythm of office life. Weekly rhythms must be intentional.
</Callout>

<Checklist title="Weekly Planning Checklist">
- [ ] Review last week's achievements and learnings
- [ ] Align individual priorities with team goals
- [ ] Schedule deep work blocks for the week
- [ ] Identify collaboration and meeting needs
- [ ] Set clear boundaries and availability
</Checklist>

<Tabs>
<Tab label="Monday - Planning">
**Individual Planning (30-60 minutes):**
- Review last week's accomplishments
- Set this week's top 3-5 priorities
- Schedule focus blocks on calendar
- Identify collaboration needs

**Team Planning Sync (30-45 minutes):**
- Review team goals and OKRs
- Each person shares top priorities
- Identify dependencies and collaboration points
- Problem-solve blockers together
- Assign action items with owners and due dates
</Tab>
<Tab label="Tuesday-Thursday - Execution">
Protected for deep work with minimal meetings.
</Tab>
<Tab label="Friday - Review">
**Individual Weekly Review (30 minutes):**
- What did I accomplish? (celebrate wins)
- What didn't get done and why? (learn without judgment)
- What did I learn about my productivity?
- What are next week's priorities?

**Team Weekly Review (45-60 minutes):**
- **Wins:** Team shares accomplishments
- **Metrics:** Review KPIs and OKR progress
- **Learnings:** What worked, what didn't, what to change
- **Appreciation:** Team members recognize each other
- **Look Ahead:** Preview next week's priorities

**Zapier's "Pair Up" Program:** Zapier runs a structured weekly review where team members pair up to discuss their week, creating accountability and cross-team connection.
</Tab>
</Tabs>

### The Retrospective Practice

<Callout type="success" title="Continuous Improvement">
Remote teams need intentional spaces to improve *how* they work together. Weekly retrospectives create this space.
</Callout>

<StepGuide title="Weekly Team Retro Format">
<StepGuideStep title="Set Context (5 min)">
- Review purpose (continuous improvement)
- Set psychological safety
</StepGuideStep>
<StepGuideStep title="What Went Well (15 min)">
- Team shares successes
- Identify what to keep doing
</StepGuideStep>
<StepGuideStep title="What Didn&apos;t Go Well (15 min)">
- Share challenges and friction points
- Focus on systems/processes, not people
</StepGuideStep>
<StepGuideStep title="What Will We Change (15 min)">
- Choose 1-2 specific improvements
- Assign owners
- Define success criteria
</StepGuideStep>
<StepGuideStep title="Close (10 min)">
- Appreciations and acknowledgments
- Next week's facilitator
</StepGuideStep>
</StepGuide>

<Accordion>
<AccordionItem title="Remote-Retro Specific Questions">
- **Communication:** What async/sync patterns worked well?
- **Documentation:** What information was hard to find?
- **Time Zones:** How did we handle cross-zone collaboration?
- **Focus Time:** Were deep work blocks respected?
- **Decision Making:** How were decisions documented and communicated?
</AccordionItem>

<AccordionItem title="GitLab&apos;s Retro Process">
- **Weekly:** Team retrospectives focused on improvement
- **Quarterly:** Company-wide retrospectives
- **Always Action-Oriented:** Every retro ends with specific, measurable actions
- **Transparency:** Retro findings shared publicly with company
</AccordionItem>

<AccordionItem title="Psychological Safety Techniques">
- **Round Robin:** Everyone speaks in turn
- **Anonymous Feedback:** Use forms for sensitive topics
- **Start with Gratitude:** Set positive tone
- **Blameless Post-Mortems:** Focus on systems, not people
- **Action-Oriented:** Always end with concrete next steps
</AccordionItem>
</Accordion>

